1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,440
 So now we're going to talk about a hashed-based implementation of our map.

2
00:00:04,440 --> 00:00:07,340
 And this is the answer to the world's most common

3
00:00:07,340 --> 00:00:09,280
 programming interview question.

4
00:00:09,280 --> 00:00:11,380
 But we're going to do hash maps and then tree maps.

5
00:00:11,380 --> 00:00:13,040
 Tree maps are harder.

6
00:00:13,040 --> 00:00:15,380
 So hash maps turn out to be beautifully simple.

7
00:00:15,380 --> 00:00:20,440
 And that's kind of the reason that everyone likes these as interview questions,

8
00:00:20,440 --> 00:00:23,400
 because the interviewer can remember the answer.

9
00:00:23,400 --> 00:00:25,380
 A tree map, they might have trouble remembering.

10
00:00:25,380 --> 00:00:29,540
 And so it's the perfect thing in an interview to say,

11
00:00:29,680 --> 00:00:32,780
 "Draw me a hash map," because they still remember the answer

12
00:00:32,780 --> 00:00:34,000
 from when they went to school.

13
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,380
 They'd have to do a little review to get the tree map right.

14
00:00:36,380 --> 00:00:38,100
 So here we go.

15
00:00:38,100 --> 00:00:41,040
 So let's talk a little bit about our hash map implementation.

16
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:42,340
 It's got a weird order.

17
00:00:42,340 --> 00:00:44,180
 And once you see the data structure internally,

18
00:00:44,180 --> 00:00:46,440
 it'll be clear why there's a weird order.

19
00:00:46,440 --> 00:00:50,640
 It is like a Python 2 dictionary, and it's like a Java hash map.

20
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:52,780
 It's very similar to both of these things.

21
00:00:52,780 --> 00:00:55,680
 I'm guessing the code we're going to write is very similar

22
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:58,780
 to when Guido made his first dictionary.

23
00:00:58,900 --> 00:01:02,080
 It's going to have an extremely fast insert and looked up.

24
00:01:02,080 --> 00:01:04,540
 Just like Python 2 dictionaries and Java hash maps,

25
00:01:04,540 --> 00:01:08,740
 it's going to be iterable like Python 2's dictionaries

26
00:01:08,740 --> 00:01:12,140
 and Java's hash maps, and it builds on linked lists.

27
00:01:12,140 --> 00:01:17,180
 Surprisingly, it's really easy to build a hash map

28
00:01:17,180 --> 00:01:19,240
 if you understand linked lists.

29
00:01:19,240 --> 00:01:25,500
 And so it's covered in chapters 6.5.1 and 6.6 in Kernighan and Ritchie.

30
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:31,100
 6.5.2 is literally the hardest part of the book.

31
00:01:31,100 --> 00:01:34,200
 And that's why we kind of start with 6.6

32
00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:36,580
 and then kind of go back to 6.5.

33
00:01:36,580 --> 00:01:40,080
 Okay, so let's take a look at our data structures

34
00:01:40,080 --> 00:01:43,240
 and how we're going to go from the list map to the hash map.

35
00:01:43,240 --> 00:01:46,300
 So our list map is pretty simple.

36
00:01:46,300 --> 00:01:49,840
 We've got the entries in the map, which are key value,

37
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:52,380
 which we've decided are going to stay public.

38
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:56,040
 We've got the pre even the next for the MapEntry,

39
00:01:56,040 --> 00:01:59,140
 which is just, you know, we're going to link these things together.

40
00:01:59,140 --> 00:02:02,380
 And then the list map itself, it's got a head and it's got a tail

41
00:02:02,380 --> 00:02:04,140
 and maybe a count and a few other things,

42
00:02:04,140 --> 00:02:07,180
 and then the methods, et cetera, because we've done encapsulation.

43
00:02:07,180 --> 00:02:12,740
 So the HashMapEntry, if you look at it, it's pretty much identical.

44
00:02:12,740 --> 00:02:14,940
 And that's because the entries in a hash map

45
00:02:14,940 --> 00:02:16,700
 are just part of a linked list.

46
00:02:16,700 --> 00:02:19,900
 The key to the hash map is there's multiple linked lists.

47
00:02:20,040 --> 00:02:23,340
 And we see that in struct hash map,

48
00:02:23,340 --> 00:02:25,840
 and underscore buckets is how many buckets we have.

49
00:02:25,840 --> 00:02:28,700
 In a more sophisticated hash map implementation,

50
00:02:28,700 --> 00:02:32,180
 we would have the number of buckets grow as size grew

51
00:02:32,180 --> 00:02:34,940
 and the list got too long, but we're going to keep that.

52
00:02:34,940 --> 00:02:36,540
 So that's called rehashing,

53
00:02:36,540 --> 00:02:39,800
 and we're going to keep that out of our conversation.

54
00:02:39,800 --> 00:02:41,300
 So what we're going to have a number of buckets,

55
00:02:41,300 --> 00:02:43,080
 and in this case, it's going to be eight.

56
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:45,080
 So those are called hash buckets.

57
00:02:45,080 --> 00:02:48,440
 And then we're going to have heads, plural,

58
00:02:48,580 --> 00:02:51,240
 we're going to have eight of them, and tails, eight of them.

59
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:55,540
 But within a particular head and a tail, it really is a hash map.

60
00:02:55,540 --> 00:02:58,200
 So as you're writing the code for the hash map,

61
00:02:58,200 --> 00:03:00,340
 go back to the list map.

62
00:03:00,340 --> 00:03:02,840
 I mean, literally copy the list map code,

63
00:03:02,840 --> 00:03:04,540
 and then change the singular to plural.

64
00:03:04,540 --> 00:03:08,200
 And you'll see some of the things I show you in the actual code.

65
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:12,040
 So if we look at how a list map looks, it's got a head,

66
00:03:12,040 --> 00:03:14,600
 and it's got a bunch of entries that have preves and necks.

67
00:03:14,600 --> 00:03:16,240
 I'm not even showing the preves and the arrows,

68
00:03:16,380 --> 00:03:19,100
 I'm just showing the necks, but assume there's always preves there,

69
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:21,140
 because it's a way for us to link things in.

70
00:03:21,140 --> 00:03:25,640
 But if you look at the hash map, so you take the actual key,

71
00:03:25,640 --> 00:03:27,680
 you run it through a hash function,

72
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:32,240
 which creates some big number, no matter how, but it is just a number.

73
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:34,600
 No matter how long the key is,

74
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:36,980
 it can be one character or 2,000 characters,

75
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:40,400
 eventually the hash runs a calculation that gives us back a number.

76
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:44,340
 Sort of a pseudo random number that has, you know, equally likely,

77
00:03:44,340 --> 00:03:46,300
 and there's a whole science of hashing.

78
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:49,500
 And then we take a modulo, and in this case, we have four buckets.

79
00:03:49,500 --> 00:03:53,280
 So we take this hash calculation, modulo four,

80
00:03:53,280 --> 00:03:56,080
 and that gives us a number from zero through three.

81
00:03:56,080 --> 00:04:00,940
 And with that number, we pick the linked list,

82
00:04:00,940 --> 00:04:03,000
 and then we add it to the linked list,

83
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:07,840
 just as if we were doing this with a linked list.

84
00:04:07,840 --> 00:04:10,940
 So once we've done the hash and we picked a bucket,

85
00:04:10,940 --> 00:04:14,540
 it really is exactly the same as a linked list.

86
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:21,200
 So a hash map with four buckets is the same as four linked lists.

87
00:04:21,200 --> 00:04:24,300
 And you pick the linked list by the hash computation.

88
00:04:24,300 --> 00:04:27,480
 And hash computation is deterministic and predictable.

89
00:04:27,480 --> 00:04:30,480
 So wherever we put D, it's going to be in bucket one.

90
00:04:30,480 --> 00:04:35,000
 We can look it up in bucket one, we can store it in bucket one, etc.

91
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:39,300
 And so for inserting M equals 90, that's going to hash into bucket two,

92
00:04:39,300 --> 00:04:41,780
 and we're going to put it in that linked list.

93
00:04:41,900 --> 00:04:47,180
 Okay, so it is beautifully simple. Now, what is a hash calculation?

94
00:04:47,180 --> 00:04:50,980
 This is actually from my Postgres for Everybody course.

95
00:04:50,980 --> 00:04:58,400
 Basically, the hash maps large data items to a single number,

96
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:00,980
 basically, and these are called hash values.

97
00:05:00,980 --> 00:05:03,040
 So the whole concept of a hash function,

98
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:06,900
 when used with a modulo, in this case, I've got 16,

99
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:13,400
 modulo 16, in this picture, it maps a big string into some fixed number

100
00:05:13,400 --> 00:05:15,600
 of buckets and often the buckets are power of two,

101
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:18,900
 but they don't have to be, it's really a modulo operation.

102
00:05:18,900 --> 00:05:24,840
 And so there's a whole science of hashing and hash functions.

103
00:05:24,840 --> 00:05:27,240
 And it turns out the hashing and hash functions

104
00:05:27,240 --> 00:05:31,600
 are a big part of security and digital signatures and all that stuff.

105
00:05:31,600 --> 00:05:36,640
 And so there are people who spend their whole lives

106
00:05:36,780 --> 00:05:39,980
 researching how to build good hash functions.

107
00:05:39,980 --> 00:05:43,740
 And so there's this SHA-256 compression function,

108
00:05:43,740 --> 00:05:46,980
 you can go look it up, you can see what's going on here

109
00:05:46,980 --> 00:05:49,440
 is like the arrows are shifting,

110
00:05:49,440 --> 00:05:52,440
 and the plus with a circle is exclusive ORs.

111
00:05:52,440 --> 00:05:56,740
 And they sort of both show you the shifting and the exclusive OR

112
00:05:56,740 --> 00:05:58,580
 and they give you a diagram of all these things

113
00:05:58,580 --> 00:06:00,780
 and they shift and exclusive OR, yada yada,

114
00:06:00,780 --> 00:06:04,800
 and they're taking the pieces of a value,

115
00:06:04,940 --> 00:06:08,100
 it's computed in a loop and updated and what they're showing you

116
00:06:08,100 --> 00:06:12,940
 is what happens each iteration through the loop.

117
00:06:12,940 --> 00:06:18,240
 And so the idea is, is we are going to take a string, string array,

118
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:20,480
 and we're going to take a number of buckets.

119
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:26,500
 And the idea of a hash is it is just some integer number.

120
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:29,800
 And we're going to go through each of the items,

121
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:31,640
 each of the characters in the string,

122
00:06:31,780 --> 00:06:35,280
 that's the 4 * * * *++,

123
00:06:35,280 --> 00:06:37,840
 and we're going to take the current value of hash,

124
00:06:37,840 --> 00:06:41,580
 in this case, we're going to shift it 3 to the left,

125
00:06:41,580 --> 00:06:43,340
 and then we're going to exclusive OR it

126
00:06:43,340 --> 00:06:44,980
 with the character we're looking at.

127
00:06:44,980 --> 00:06:49,480
 So you can say, shift 3, exclusive OR, shift 3, exclusive OR.

128
00:06:49,480 --> 00:06:51,800
 So you can think of it as like an accumulation,

129
00:06:51,800 --> 00:06:55,240
 but the exclusive OR is a nice form of accumulation

130
00:06:55,240 --> 00:06:59,700
 in that it increases the randomness,

131
00:07:00,340 --> 00:07:02,100
 the pseudo-randomness of this thing.

132
00:07:02,100 --> 00:07:07,540
 And so exclusive OR just turns out to be a super valuable calculation.

133
00:07:07,540 --> 00:07:10,280
 And so this loop is going to run so many times.

134
00:07:10,280 --> 00:07:12,680
 And so we're going to print it out, you're going to see the hex,

135
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:15,440
 if we're just taking the letters HI,

136
00:07:15,440 --> 00:07:19,740
 you can see kind of the internal hash value growing and changing,

137
00:07:19,740 --> 00:07:24,240
 and you can kind of see it going from right to left as it sort of grows.

138
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:27,600
 And there's new data being put in bitwise,

139
00:07:27,600 --> 00:07:30,080
 it's a bit, you know, bit exclusive OR.

140
00:07:30,200 --> 00:07:34,000
 But at the very end, it says return hash percent buckets,

141
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:37,100
 which takes the modulo operator of the number of buckets.

142
00:07:37,100 --> 00:07:39,540
 And in this case, I'm going to be using eight buckets

143
00:07:39,540 --> 00:07:41,400
 just to run the hash function, right?

144
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:43,740
 Give me the bucket for this string,

145
00:07:43,740 --> 00:07:47,580
 so you can see me running different things on the right-hand side

146
00:07:47,580 --> 00:07:49,940
 and getting back the ultimate final bucket.

147
00:07:49,940 --> 00:07:53,540
 So HI goes in bucket one, Hello goes in bucket seven,

148
00:07:53,540 --> 00:07:55,680
 and world goes into bucket four.

149
00:07:55,800 --> 00:08:01,800
 This is really inspired by, you know, the shifting and the masking,

150
00:08:01,800 --> 00:08:05,000
 but I've simplified it so you can kind of see what's going on.

151
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:09,480
 And in our particular hash, it's good enough for our purposes.

152
00:08:09,480 --> 00:08:11,900
 But it's probably going to have collisions

153
00:08:11,900 --> 00:08:14,340
 when treated against a whole series of random data,

154
00:08:14,340 --> 00:08:15,780
 it's not going to be as good.

155
00:08:15,780 --> 00:08:21,640
 And that's where a fancy hash like SHA-256 would be helpful.

156
00:08:21,640 --> 00:08:25,540
 So now that we understand the basic data structures,

157
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:29,200
 and how hashing functions work, let's, up next,

158
00:08:29,200 --> 00:08:31,800
 we're going to take a look at actually building a hash map,

159
00:08:31,800 --> 00:08:37,040
 or at least adapting our list map and turning it into a hash map.

